text: Journal of Basic Microbiology 2010, 50, 135 – 142  Isolation, structure elucidation and biological activity   of angucycline antibiotics   from an epiphytic yew streptomycete  Michal Maruna1, Maria Sturdikova1, Tibor Liptaj2, Andrej Godany3, Marta Muckova4, Milan Certik1,  Nadezda Pronayova2 and Bohumil Proksa5  1 Department of Biochemical Technology, Institute of Biotechnology and Food Science, Faculty of Chemical  and Food Technology, Slovak University of Technology in Bratislava, Slovak Republic  2 Department of NMR and Mass Spectroscopy, Faculty of Chemical and Food Technology,   3 Institute of Molecular Biology, Slovak Academy of Sciences, Bratislava, Slovak Republic  4 hameln-rds a.s., Modra, Slovak Republic  5 Zentiva a.s., Hlohovec, Slovak Republic

In the course of study of epiphytic microorganisms occurring on the surface of roots of Taxus  baccata  L.  a  new  strain  Streptomyces  sp.  AC113  was  isolated.  According  to  16S  ribosomal  DNA- based  identification  the  new  strain  is  99%  identical  with  Streptomyces  flavidofuscus.  This  strain  cultivated in an arginine glycerol medium produced three major metabolites identified as (–)-8- O-methyltetrangomycin (1), 8-O-methyltetrangulol (2) and 8-O-methyl-7-deoxo-7-hydroxytetran- gomycin (3). The chemical structures of these angucyclines were elucidated by 1D and 2D NMR  as  well  as  by  mass  spectrometry.  Isolated  angucycline  metabolites  showed  significant  anti- microbial  activity  against  Bacillus  cereus  and  Listeria  mocytogenes.  Cytotoxic  activities  of  com- pounds  1,  2  and  3  against  four  cell  lines  (B16,  HT-29  and  non  –  tumor  V79,  L929)  were  evaluated.  Compound  3  was  the  most  potent  anticancer  agents  with  IC50  0.054  μg/ml  against  cell line B16.  Keywords: Angucycline / Streptomyces / Nocardiopsis dassonvillei / Tetrangomycin  Received: July 15, 2009; accepted: October 06, 2009  DOI 10.1002/jobm.200900227

Microbial  secondary  metabolites  represent  a  large  source  of  compounds  with  various  structures  and  po- tent biological activities. Polyketides (including angucy- cline)  of  them  comprise  one  of  the  largest  families  of  secondary metabolites found in nature. The term angu- cycline refers to a characteristic four-ring frame (tetra- cyclic benz[a]anthracene structural moiety) arranged in  an angular manner, and this family includes more than  one hundred secondary metabolites of microbial origin. KGaA, Weinheim  Slovak University of Technology in Bratislava, Slovak Republic  The angucycline group metabolites have been shown to  have a variety of biological activities, such as antibacte- rial  and  antitumor  activity,  and  some  act  as  inhibitors  of  oxidative  enzymes.  Selected  angucyclines  are  also  potent inhibitors of blood platelet aggregation [1]. Fila- mentous soil bacteria belonging to the genus Streptomy- ces are significant source of bioactive products. Also the  majority  of  metabolites  with  angucycline  structure  have been isolated from Streptomyces [2 – 5].

In the course of our screening program for bioactive  natural  products  was  isolated  epiphytic  actinomycete  strain from Taxus baccata. Previously isolated strain was  screened  for  the  production  of  high  potent  anticancer  secondary  metabolites.  Identification  of  metabolites  produced  by  isolated  strain,  together  with  results  of  biological  tests  performed  with  three  angucycline  me- tabolites is presented in this paper.

Cultivation of streptomycete isolate  Streptomyces sp. AC113 is a wild epiphytic type, isolated  from  rhizosphera  of  Taxus  baccata  L.  The  isolate  was  maintained  on  Actinomycetes  isolation  agar  (HiMedia,  India) at 4 °C and the lyophilisate of this strain is stored  in  collection  of  microorganisms  at  the  Department  of  Biochemical Technology (Faculty of Chemical and Food  Technology,  Slovak  University  of  Technology  in  Brati- slava, Slovak Republic).    The  seed  cultures  were  prepared  by  cultivating  the  spores  (1 × 107 spores/ml)  in  500 ml  flasks  that  con- tained  100 ml  of  Actinomycetes  Broth  (HiMedia,  India)  and were shaken at 180 rpm at 28 °C for 48 h. For pro- duction  culture,  10 ml  of  the  seed  culture  was  inocu- lated  into  100 ml  of  the  production  arginine-glycerol  medium in 500 ml Erlenmeyer flasks. The initial pH of  the  flask  culture  was  adjusted  to  7.0  and  the  flasks  were  incubated  at  28 °C  in  the  dark  with  shaking  at  140 rpm.    Production medium arginine-glycerol contained (g/l):  D-xylose  20 g;  L-arginine  1 g;  glycerol  12,5 g;  K2HPO4  1 g;  NaCl  1 g;  Fe2(SO4)3 ⋅ 6 H2O  0,01 g;  CuSO4 ⋅ 5 H2O  1 mg,  ZnSO4 ⋅ 7 H2O  1 mg,  MnSO4 ⋅ H2O  1 mg,  the  pH  was adjusted to 7.0.

Identification of streptomycete isolate  Streptomyces  sp.  AC113,  a  wild  epiphytic  type,  isolated  from  rhizosphera  of  Taxus  baccata  L.,  was  checked  for  purity and its taxonomic properties were examined on  the basis of 16S rDNA sequence. For DNA isolation the  spores  were  inoculated  into  10  ml  of  Nutrient  Broth  2  (Imuna,  Slovakia)  and  cultivated  at  28 °C  overnight.  Two ml of the culture were then inoculated into 30 ml  of  YEME  medium  [6]  containing  34%  of  sucrose  and  0.8% of glycine. After 8 h of cultivation lysozyme (final  concentration  2 mg/ml)  and  RNAse  A  (final  concentra- tion 2 mg/ml) was added to a and the culture was culti- vated  for  the  next  30 h  [7].  Resulting  mixture  was  ex- tracted twice with phenol-chloroform mixture (1 : 1) and  then  twice  with  chloroform.  Obtained  DNA  was  pre- cipitated  by  ethanol,  washed  and  finally  dissolved  in  1 ml  of  sterile  TE  buffer  Quality  and  quantity  of  DNA  was checked by spectrophotometry.    The  16S  rDNA  genes  were  amplified  by  from  the  genomic  DNA  to  obtain  PCR  products  for  sequencing  analysis.  PCR  an  appropriate  band  on  agarose  gel,  and  also  Universal  primers  targeting  16S  rDNA  bacterial  sequences were used for PCR: forward primer (UniF 5′- AGAGTTTGATCCTGGCTGAG-3′),  and  reverse  primer  (UniR 5′-ACGGCTACCTTGTTACGACTT-3′). PCR reactions  © 2010 WILEY-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim

were performed in a final volume of 20 μl. The reaction  mixture  contained:  0.5 U  DyNAzymeTM  DNA  poly- merase,  0.4 μl  10 mmol/l  dNTP  Mix,  2 μl  Optimized  DyNAzymeTM  10×  reaction  buffer  (all  Finnzymes),  and  1 μl  of  each  primer  (25 μmol/l).  The  amplification  pro- gram consisted of denaturation (5 min, 96 °C), 30 cycles  of denaturation (1 min, 96 °C), annealing (1 min, 55 °C)  and extension (2 min, 72 °C), followed by a final exten- sion (8 min, 72 °C). Ten μl of PCR-amplified product was  analyzed  by  electrophoresis  on  0.9%  agarose  gel  and  stained  with  ethidium  bromide;  this  was  done  in  1×  BBE (in mmol/l: boric acid 650, disodium tetraborate 29,  EDTA  250;  pH 7.8).  Under  these  conditions  genomic  DNA (300 ng/μl) was used as a template.    DNA  amplification  and  sequencing  of  16S  rRNA  genes of isolate were carried out using established pro- cedures  [8].  The  resultant  16S  rRNA  gene  sequences  were  aligned  against  already  aligned  sequences  of  the  type  strains  of  Streptomyces  species,  retrieved  from  the  RDP  database,  using  the  CLUSTAL  algorithm  incorpo- rated in BioEdit program [9]. A rooted phylogenetic tree  was  inferred  using  the  neighbour-joining  tree-making  algorithm  and  an  evolutionary  distance  matrix  after  Kimura  two-parameter  method.  All  analyses  were  car- ried out using MEGA 3 software [10].

Fatty acid analysis  Mycelium  was  harvested  by  centrifugation  and  wash  twice  with  distilled  water.  The  lipids  were  extracted  two times with chloroform-methanol (2 : 1 v/v). Extracts  were  mixed  with  0.97%  solution  of  KCl  in  amount  of  1.20 volume fold of chloroform-methanol, stirred, cen- trifuged and chloroform (bottom) phase was separated,  dried and evaporated under reduced pressure.    Fatty  acids  of  total  lipids  were  analysed  as  their  methyl  esters  (prepared  according  to  methods  of  Christoperson  and  Glass  [11])  by  gas  chromatography  (GC-6890  N,  Agilent  Technologies)  using  a  capillary  (60 m × 0.25 mm,  thickness  column  DB-23  0.25 μm, Agilent Technologies) and a FID detector (con- stant flow, hydrogen 40 ml/min, air 450 ml/min, 250 °C)  under  a  temperature  gradient  (170 °C  hold  for  6 min;  170 − 200 °C at program rate 10 °C/min; 200 °C hold for  5 min;  200 − 220 °C  at  program  rate  5 °C/min;  220 − 240 °C  at  program  rate  2 °C/min;  240 °C  hold  for  10 min)  with  hydrogen  as  carrier  gas  (flow  2.5 ml/min,  velocity  57 cm/s,  pressure  220 kPa)  and  a  split  ratio  of  1/20  (Inlets:  heater  230 °C;  hydrogen  flow  51 ml/min   for  2 min,  then  hydrogen  flow  20 ml/min;  pressure  220 kPa). The fatty acid methylester peaks were identi- fied  by  authentic  standards  of  C4 − C24  fatty  acid  me- thylesters  mixture  (Supelco

,  then  hydrogen  flow  20 ml/min;  pressure  220 kPa). The fatty acid methylester peaks were identi- fied  by  authentic  standards  of  C4 − C24  fatty  acid  me- thylesters  mixture  (Supelco,  USA)  and  evaluated  by

To identify  the unknown peaks in lipid structures, GC-MS analysis  of  fatty  acid  methyl  esters  was  also  performed.  The  samples  were  introduced  through  gas  chromatograph  (GC-6890  N,  Agilent  Technologies)  and  separated  as  mentioned  above.  The  effluent  was  detected  by  total  ionization  monitoring  with  a  mass  selective  detector  (MS-5975,  Agilent  Technologies).  The  electron  impact  mass  spectra  were  set  at  a  voltage  of  70 eV.  All  peaks  were  evaluated  by  MSD  ChemStation  E.00.00.202  (Agilent  Technologies)  with  combination  of  NIST  Mass  Spectral  Search  Program  version  2.0 d  (Agilent  Tech- nologies).  Identification and isolation of metabolites  The  culture  medium  was  filtered,  filtrate  (6 l,  pH  6.0)  was  extracted  with  ethyl  acetate,  organic  layer  dried  with anhydrous Na2SO4 was concentrated, and the resi- due  was  distributed  between  heptane  and  aqueous  methanol  (10%  water).  Methanol  layer  was  separated  and  after  evaporation  2 g  of  raw  extract  was  obtained.  Crude  extract  was  processed  by  chromatographic  frac- tionation.  The  fractions  collected  from  the  semiprepa- rative  chromatography  were  further  analyzed  using  standardized analytical methods.

KGaA, Weinheim  IR:  FT-IR  Nicolet  Magna  750  Spectrometer,  KBr  tech- Antibiotic bioassay  The  microorganisms  as  follows  were  used  in  antibiotic  assay:  Pseudomonas  aeruginosa  CCM  3955,  Staphylococcus  aureus  CCM  3953,  Escherichia  coli  CCM  3988  (Czech  Col- lection  of  Microorganisms,  Brno,  Czech  Republic),  Lis- teria  monocytogenes  NCTC  4886  (National  Collection  of  Type Cultures, London, United Kingdom), Bacillus subtilis  CCM  2216,  Bacillus  cereus  (isolated  from  milk,  Depart- ment  of  Food  Technology,  Faculty  of  Chemical  and  Food  Technology,  Slovak  University  of  Technology,  Bratislava,  Slovakia)    and  they  were  cultured  on  Brain  Heart Infusion (BHI) broth (Merck).    The  antibacterial  effect  was  assayed  by  a  microdilu- tion  method  in  96-well  microtitration  plates.  The  cul- ture  was  grown  at  (37 ± 1) °C  under  aerobic  conditions  for 16 – 18 h. The initial density of bacterial strains was  approx.  107  CFU/ml.  This  bacterial  suspension  (180 μl)  was added to 20 μl of the tested plants extracts solution  and  cultured  for  12  h  stationary  in  a  thermostat  at  (37 ± 1) °C.  The  time  course  of  absorbance  (A630),  was  then determined in triplicates. Gentamicin was used as  standard antibiotic compound.

Cell lines and culture  B16  mouse  melanoma  cell  line  (Cancer  Research  Insti- tute  of  Slovak  Academy  of  Sciences,  Bratislava,  Slova- kia)  and  HT-29  human  colon  adenocarcinoma  cells  (European  Collection  of  Cell  Cultures,  Salisbury,  Eng- land)  were  incubated  at  37 °C  in  humidified  atmos- phere  with  5%  CO2  in  a  complete  culture  medium  (Modified  Eagles  Medium,  MEM,  Biowhittaker)  supple- mented with 10% of fetal calf serum (Biowhittaker) and  McCoys 5A (Gibco) supplemented with 10% of fetal calf  serum for HT-29 cell line, respectively.    Non-tumor  Chinese  hamster  V79  cells  (European  Collection  of  Cell  Cultures,  Salisbury,  England)    were  incubated  at  37 °C  in  humidified  atmosphere  with  5%  CO2 in a complete culture medium (Dulbecco Modified  Eagles  Medium,  DMEM,  Biowhittaker)  supplemented  with 10% of fetal calf serum (Biowhittaker).    Non-tumor  mouse  fibroblast  cells  L  929  (European  Collection  of  Cell  Cultures,  Salisbury,  England)    were  incubated  at  37 °C  in  humidified  atmosphere  with  5%  CO2  in  a  complete  culture  medium  (Modified  Eagles  Medium,  MEM,  Biowhittaker)  supplemented  with  10%  of fetal calf serum (Biowhittaker).

Methyl thiazole tetrazolium cell viability test (MTT)  This  test  was  performed  according  to  Mosmann  [12]  with  slight  modifications.  Tumor  cells  (4 × 104 cells/ml  for  B16  cells  and  1 × 105 cells/ml  for  HT-29  cells),  non  tumor  cells  (5 × 103 cells/ml  for  V  79  cells  and  L  929  Biological active angucycline  cells)  were  incubated  in  a  96-well  microtiter  plates  in  100 μl  of  complete  medium.  After  24 h  incubation  in  humidified  atmosphere  at  37 °C  containing  5%  CO2,  diluted  extracts  were  added  in  each  well  (final  volume  of  100 μl).  After  next  24 h  100 μl  of  medium  was  re- moved  and  100 μl  of  MTT  (5 mg/ml  PBS)  were  added.  After  3 h  incubation  at  37 °C 100 μl  medium  was  care- fully  removed  from  each  well  and  replaced  with  HCl- Isopropanol.  After  10 – 15 min  incubation  at  37 °C,  the  solubilized  formazan  produced  by  metabolically  active  cells was measured at 540 and 630 nm.

Characterization of producing strain  Epiphytic actinomycete strain from Taxus baccata, Strep- tomyces  sp.  AC113  is  an  aerobe,  Gram-positive,  non- motile  actinomycete  that  forms  extensively  branched  aerial  and  substrate  hyphae.  Short  or  long,  straight  to  flexuous  chains  of  smooth  surfaced  spores  are  evident  on  the  aerial  hyphae.  The  aerial  mycelium  is  white  in  colour and the substrate mycelium appears light cream  when  grown  on  Actinomyces  isolation  agar  (HiMedia,  India). Further characteristic of the strain was based on  fatty  acid  profile  of  intracellular  lipids.  As  Fig. 1  dis- plays, cellular fatty acids are composed mainly of hexa- Figure 1. Other anteiso- and  iso-  fatty  acids  (C15,  C17  and  C18)  were  also  detected.  Such  composition  of  presented  cellular  fatty  acids  has  also been reported for actinomycetes [13, 14].    The  optimum  growth  of  the  studied  strain  was  ob- served at 28 °C and it utilized various monosaccharides  (D-ribose,  D-arabinose,  D-xylose,  D-glucose,  D-fructose),  (D-trehalose.  D-maltose,  D-saccharose)  disaccharides  and polyols (dulcitol and D-mannitol) as well. Streptomy- ces  sp.  AC113  displayed  low  lipolytic  activity  as  con- firmed test with tributyrin medium.    The  obtained  nucleotide  sequences  of  the  nearly  complete  16S  rRNA  genes  of  the  streptomycete  isolate  AC113  was  deposited  in  the  GenBank  database  under  the  accession  Nos:  FJ001763.1.  According  to  16S  ribo- somal  DNA-based  identification  the  strain  Streptomyces  sp.  AC113  is  99%  identical  with  Streptomyces  flavidofus- cus.  However,  recently  Streptomyces  flavidofuscus  was  reclassified  as  Nocardiopsis  dassonvillei  subsp.  dassonvillei  [15].

Isolated  compound  1  (Fig. 2)  afforded  a  [M]+  peak  at  m/z  336  accompanied  by  peaks  corresponding  to  frag- ments  M – H2O  and  M – H2O – CH3  only.  Compound  1  according to IR with bands at 1696, 1668 and 1595 cm–1  contains  carbonyl  groups  conjugated  with  unsaturated  bonds  which  in  UV  spectrum  were  manifested  by  ab- sorption  bands  at  263  and  374 nm.  Structure  of  1  was  unambiguously  confirmed  by  NMR  techniques,  espe- cially by COSY, HSQC and HMBC experiments (Table 1)  and according to these data compound 1 is identified as  8-O-methyltetrangomycin.  Because  the  isolated  com- pound  revealed  the  same  optical  rotation  as  that  one  published  for  [16],  the  absolute  configuration  of  compound  1  was  3R  [17]. Biological activities  The  extracts  of  the  streptomycete  strain  grown  in  the  liquid  culture  media  exhibit  cytotoxic  activities  when  tested  in  vitro  against  B16  mouse  melanoma  and  HT29  human  colon  adenocarcinoma  cells.  Chromatographic  separation  of  the  extracts  yielded  natural  products,  of  which  five  showed  cytotoxic  activity.  Cytotoxicity  of  three of them separated and purified metabolites is pre- sented in Table 3. Among the metabolites tested against  cancer  cell  lines,  IC50  values  varied  from  0.054  to  66.9 μg/ml.  Compound  3  was  most  potent  against  B16  and HT29, IC50 0.054 μg/ml and 8.58 μg/ml, respectively.  Table 2. In vivo antitumor activities of angucyclines have also  been reported for the kerriamycins [28] and vineomycin  [29].  The  aquayamycin  type  metabolite  aggreticin  and  the  saquayamycins,  were  noted  to  inhibit  doxorubicin- resistant  and  adriamycinresistant  cell  lines,  respec- tively. The suggested mode of action for the antitumor  activity  of  this  group  is  DNA  alkylation  [30].  Landomy- cin  E  [31]  or  chemomycin  A  [32]  were  also  active  in  cytotoxicity tests.    Furthemore,  antibacterial  activities  of  compounds  1,  2 and 3 were also investigated. The active antimicrobial  compounds  of  Streptomyces  isolate  were  tested  against  six  bacteria.  The  minimal  inhibitory  concentration  (MIC)  and  inhibitory  concentration  IC50  values  are  pre- sented in Table 2. Among the metabolites, compound 2  was  highly  active,  MIC  values  in  the  range  of  0.51 – 1.03 μg/ml  were  observed  against  tested  bacteria.  The  positive  control,  gentamicin  showed  MIC  values  ranging  from  26.2  to  78.6 μg/ml.  Metabolites  1  and  3  showed  similar  antibiotic  activity  against  both  G +  and  G – bacteria in presented antimicrobial assay.    Many  angucyclinones  so  far  isolated  were  weakly  active  against  G+  and  G–  bacteria,  e.g.  EI-1507-1  inhib- ited  growth  of  Enterococcus  faecium,  Bacillus  subtilis  and  Proteus  vulgaris  with  MIC  values  of  120,  60  and  60  mM,  respectively  [32]. Concluding remarks  The  results  of  the  present  study  revealed  that  actino- mycete strain Streptomyces sp. AC113 isolated from Taxus  baccata is 99% identical to Streptomyces flavidofuscus (new  name  N.  dassonvillei  subsp.  Dassonvillei).
